The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, May 11, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 OM Kotak Mahindra Life Insurance Ltd has increased its share capital base by Rs 30.25 crore to Rs 233.66 crore to augment resources for business development. The company promoters, Kotak Mahindra Bank Ltd (74 per cent) and Old Mutual (26 per cent stake)  have brought additional funds in proportion to their stake. As the company undertakes more risk, prudent capital adequacy norms require us to add more capital, managing director Shivaji Dam said. 																								 K Sera Sera, a film production company, has reported a turnover of Rs 24 crore and a profit after tax of Rs 3.57 crore for 2003-04. The company, having a tie-up with Varma Corporation, declared a dividend of 10 per cent for the year, a release said. The company produced three hindi movies last fiscal and was entering into partnerships for making TV serials. 																								 HCL Technologies has entered into a strategic tie-up with IBM Rational, a division of IBM, to strengthen its software development capabilities. As part of the agreement, IBM will set up a competency centre for HCL Technologies at its Gurgaon facility to assist the companys software development team to adapt and absorb future enhancements in Rational technologies, an IBM release said.																								 Broadvision Inc has launched its business process management solutions in India, which it has developed in partnership with Infogain. Broadvision process is an enterprise software application which energises e-business through transformation of people-intensive processes into web-based application services, Giuseppe Kobayashi, chairman (Japan and Asia Pacific) Broadvision Inc, said.																								 Mahindra British Telecom (MBT) has entered into an agreement with Syntegra, British Telecommunications Plcs consulting and system integration business, to market IT solutions for the global telecommunications sector. The partnership leverages Syntegras capabilities in system integration and programme management with MBTs domain and business process expertise. 																								 Bank of Baroda has revised its interest rates on foreign currency non-resident (bank) deposits with effect from April 28. The interest rates have gone up to 1.46 per cent (1.36 per cent earlier) for dollar deposits of tenure of one year and up to two years, BoB said. For deposit with tenures of two years and up to three years, the new rate is 2.37 per cent (2.12 per cent) and 2.85 per cent (2.72 per cent), respectively.																								 Nucleus Software, a banking products software company, will hire 200 people by the end of 2004, besides investing Rs 7 crore for its upcoming facility at Noida to house 700 professionals. We will hire people for global operations, including India. Our upcoming facility in Noida is slated to be operational in July, MD Vishnu Dusad said. ADVERTISEMENT
